dashboard.definition:
{
	"title": "Drop indexed fields",
	"description": "",
	"inputs": {},
	"defaults": {
		"dataSources": {
			"ds.search": {
				"options": {
					"queryParameters": {}
				}
			},
			"ds.spl2": {
				"options": {
					"queryParameters": {}
				}
			}
		},
		"visualizations": {
			"global": {
				"showProgressBar": true
			}
		}
	},
	"visualizations": {
		"viz_markdown": {
			"type": "splunk.markdown",
			"options": {
				"markdown": "# Problem statement\nSplunk provides a parsing options for reading structured data `INDEXED_EXTRACTIONS` which can primarily be applied to `CSV` and `JSON` data. Both of these options use a parser to extract the structured data and writes attribute value pairs into the `_meta` string to appear as indexed fields. This allows the user to accelarate `_raw` search with `TERM()` or use the SQL like `tstats` command on your data. Doing this can improve performance by more than 40 times.However the disadvance of such an approach is buckets sizes can significantly increase due to the extra entiries in the `tsidx` file. This can be expecially problematic when there is large number of CSV columns as this leads to a correspondingly large number of entitires in your lexicon. In extreme cases enabling `INDEXED_CSV` can more than double your bucket size and can comprise your retention, especially if your sized with the rule of thumb described in the documentation [Estimate your storage requirements](https://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/Splunk/8.0.6/Capacity/Estimateyourstoragerequirements)\n\n## Existing solution\nIf you have a large number of columns you are often forced to use search time enrichement instead of `INDEXED_EXTRACTIONS` and this impacts your uses cases and performance. You may choose to use a datamodel to create a smaller data set for effcient searching, which in turn is expensive on CPU usage.\n\n### INDEXED_EXTRACTIONS options\n\n    INDEXED_EXTRACTIONS = <CSV|TSV|PSV|W3C|JSON|HEC>\n    * The type of file that Splunk software should expect for a given source\n    type, and the extraction and/or parsing method that should be used on the file.\n    * The following values are valid for 'INDEXED_EXTRACTIONS':\n    CSV  - Comma separated value format\n    TSV  - Tab-separated value format\n    PSV  - pipe (\"|\")-separated value format\n    W3C  - World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) Extended Log File Format\n    JSON - JavaScript Object Notation format\n    HEC  - Interpret file as a stream of JSON events in the same format\n            as the HTTP Event Collector (HEC) input.\n    * These settings change the defaults for other settings in this subsection\n    to appropriate values, specifically for these formats.\n    * The HEC format lets events overried many details on a per-event basis, such\n    as the destination index. Use this value to read data which you know to be\n    well-formatted and safe to index with little or no processing, such as\n    data generated by locally written tools.\n    * Default: not set\n\nSource [props.conf](https://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/Splunk/8.0.6/Admin/Propsconf)\n\n## Alternative approach \nWith the introduction of `INGEST_EVAL` we can easily remove indexed fields from the `_meta` string. This allows us to keep the most important columns as indexed fields, and then use search time extraction for the less important ones. This hybrid approach allows us to keep performance of indexed fields, while keeping bucket size down.\n\n### Example data\nTo demonstrate how `INGEST_EVAL` can resolve the issue this application generates some sample data. Notice the column names and the associated values\n\n    time,primary_key,primary_value,repeated_field,random_nonsense,long_payload\n    2020-08-30 14:53:17.245855,0x97a5,625362,same silly value,b5c93b49-37e6-4d63-9dfe-447bbed8b128,splunk> IT like you mean it \n    2020-08-30 17:20:19.180806,0xb8f8,172464,same silly value,bc4a273f-9238-4f16-815c-55903f4dfe0d,Splunk> 4TW \n    2020-08-30 23:39:11.662594,0xe1cd,695140,same silly value,94447247-ce80-44a2-a788-3a539fe0ee7d,\"Splunk> see the forest, and the trees \"\n    2020-08-31 00:23:52.489584,0xeb4a,374488,same silly value,1ec2f016-cc9b-4c54-ad30-f187f47dafda,splunk> this way: Run-D.M.C. \n    2020-08-31 00:38:50.033850,0x8063,455774,same silly value,469fc7c9-b9c6-4582-8afe-e222fcad94fe,Splunk> All batbelt. No tights. \n    2020-08-31 07:58:40.252550,0xd538,884285,same silly value,074e9326-4c1c-4d39-a0e2-25fbf7c59a0c,splunk> Caught me on the server - Wasn't me. \n    2020-08-31 08:34:48.438904,0xc5b0,30242,same silly value,af7d0326-2edb-40be-bb9e-25989971ad61,splunk> because ninjas are too busy \n    2020-08-31 12:53:47.761629,0xb179,731284,same silly value,b717906c-262c-4375-bdbb-4b49b9a9c1bd,splunk> Chasing tail since 2003 \n    2020-08-31 17:11:42.791025,0xaf46,808337,same silly value,f376d805-c536-4961-9658-c941ed682177,splunk> We line break for regular expressions \n\n### How we will handle the columns\n\n* `time` - Contains the field containing the time stamp, we need this for _time\n* `primary_key` - Contains the primary field, this is a perfect field for an indexed field\n* `primary_value` - Contains the primary vaoue, this is a perfect field for an indexed field\n* `repeated_field` - The same value every time, no value to this field at all, we can just drop it\n* `random_nonsense` - Some random nonsense with high cardinality, this would bloat tsidx\n* `long_payload` - This is some random log messages, this would make an awful indexed field\n\n### Steps\n\n1. Set props to load data with `INDEXED_EXTRACTIONS=CSV`\n    1. Set the time field to in the `time` column\n    1. Set the format for the time field\n1. Create use `INGEST_EVAL` to assign `null()` using the overite assignment operator `:=` to any index field we wanted remove\n    1. Drop, `repeated_field`, `random_nonsense` and `long_payload`\n1. Create a search time lookup (i.e. regex) to extract the fields we removed as indexed fields\n    1. Use regex to extract `random_nonsense` and `long_payload` at search time\n"
			}
		},
		"viz_raw_chart": {
			"type": "splunk.line",
			"dataSources": {
				"primary": "ds_raw_chart"
			},
			"options": {},
			"showProgressBar": true,
			"title": "This chart is calculated via raw search for versatility"
		},
		"viz_tstats_chart": {
			"type": "splunk.line",
			"dataSources": {
				"primary": "ds_tstats_chart"
			},
			"options": {},
			"showProgressBar": true,
			"title": "This chart is calculated via tstats for performance"
		},
		"viz_compare_table": {
			"type": "splunk.table",
			"dataSources": {
				"primary": "ds_compare_table"
			},
			"options": {
				"drilldown": "none"
			},
			"showProgressBar": true,
			"title": "This table shows the indexed fields and the search time fields side by side"
		},
		"viz_conf_props": {
			"type": "splunk.markdown",
			"options": {
				"markdown": "### props.conf\n\nFrom `default/props.conf` \u2014 verbatim:\n\n```ini\n# Example: stripping unwanted indexed fields out of a CSV-parsed source.\n[drop_indexed_fields]\n# Timestamp comes from the `time` column; we drop that column below.\nTIMESTAMP_FIELDS=time\nINDEXED_EXTRACTIONS = CSV\n# Drop the unwanted columns and the noisy date_* fields.\nTRANSFORMS-drop_fields = drop_indexed_fields-drop_useless_columns, shared-drop_useless_time_fields\n# Re-surface the dropped columns at search time (only works in this app).\nEXTRACT-removed-columns= [^,]+,[^,]+,[^,]+,(?<random_nonsense>[^,]+),(?<long_payload>[^,]+)\n```\n"
			}
		},
		"viz_conf_transforms": {
			"type": "splunk.markdown",
			"options": {
				"markdown": "### transforms.conf\n\nFrom `default/transforms.conf` \u2014 verbatim:\n\n```ini\n# To drop a field from _meta we have to overwrite it; := does the assignment.\n[drop_indexed_fields-drop_useless_columns]\nINGEST_EVAL= time:=null(), repeated_field:=null(), random_nonsense:=null(), long_payload:=null()\n```\n"
			}
		}
	},
	"dataSources": {
		"ds_raw_chart": {
			"name": "Raw search timechart",
			"type": "ds.search",
			"options": {
				"query": "index=\"ingest_eval_examples_*\" sourcetype=drop_indexed_fields primary_key::* \n| timechart span=1d sum(primary_value) as sum_primary",
				"queryParameters": {
					"earliest": "0",
					"latest": ""
				}
			}
		},
		"ds_tstats_chart": {
			"name": "tstats timechart",
			"type": "ds.search",
			"options": {
				"query": "| tstats sum(primary_value) as sum_primary where index=ingest_eval_examples* sourcetype=drop_indexed_fields by _time span=1day",
				"queryParameters": {
					"earliest": "0",
					"latest": ""
				}
			}
		},
		"ds_compare_table": {
			"name": "Side-by-side table",
			"type": "ds.search",
			"options": {
				"query": "index=\"ingest_eval_examples_*\" sourcetype=drop_indexed_fields primary_key::*\n| table _time primary_key primary_value repeated_field random_nonsense long_payload",
				"queryParameters": {
					"earliest": "0",
					"latest": ""
				}
			}
		}
	},
	"layout": {
		"globalInputs": [],
		"layoutDefinitions": {
			"layout_1": {
				"type": "grid",
				"options": {
					"width": 1440,
					"height": 250
				},
				"structure": [
					{
						"item": "viz_markdown",
						"type": "block",
						"position": {
							"x": 0,
							"y": 0,
							"w": 720,
							"h": 800
						}
					},
					{
						"item": "viz_raw_chart",
						"type": "block",
						"position": {
							"x": 720,
							"y": 0,
							"w": 720,
							"h": 400
						}
					},
					{
						"item": "viz_tstats_chart",
						"type": "block",
						"position": {
							"x": 720,
							"y": 400,
							"w": 720,
							"h": 400
						}
					},
					{
						"item": "viz_compare_table",
						"type": "block",
						"position": {
							"x": 0,
							"y": 800,
							"w": 1440,
							"h": 500
						}
					},
					{
						"item": "viz_conf_props",
						"type": "block",
						"position": {
							"x": 0,
							"y": 1300,
							"w": 720,
							"h": 480
						}
					},
					{
						"item": "viz_conf_transforms",
						"type": "block",
						"position": {
							"x": 720,
							"y": 1300,
							"w": 720,
							"h": 480
						}
					}
				]
			}
		},
		"options": {
			"submitButton": false
		},
		"tabs": {
			"items": [
				{
					"label": "New tab",
					"layoutId": "layout_1"
				}
			]
		}
	},
	"applicationProperties": {
		"hideEdit": false,
		"hideExport": false
	}
}
